{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}} {{Infobox engineer |image = Sir Arthur John Dorman (1848-1931).jpg |image_size = 150px |caption = Bromide print by [[Walter Stoneman]] for [[National Portrait Gallery, London]] |name = Sir Arthur John Dorman, Bt |honorific_suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]] |nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]] |citizenship = [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]] |birth_date ={{birth date|df=yes|1848|8|8}} |birth_place = [[Ashford, Kent|Ashford]], [[Kent]], England |death_date ={{Death date and age|df=yes|1931|2|9|1848|8|8}} |death_place = [[Nunthorpe]], [[Middlesbrough]], England |education = [[Christ's Hospital]] |spouse = |parents = Charles Dorman, Emma Page |children = |discipline = [[Industrialist]], [[Dorman Long]] |institutions = |practice_name = |significant_projects = |significant_design = |significant_awards = }}
'''Sir Arthur John Dorman, 1st Baronet''' [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]] (8 August 1848 – 12 February 1931) was an important [[United Kingdom|British]] [[industrialist]].
==Early life== He was born at [[Ashford, Kent|Ashford]] in [[Kent]] the son of Charles Dorman and Emma Page and educated at [[Christ's Hospital]], then situated in [[Newgate]], London.
==Career== He was sent, at the age of 22, by his family to work at a [[Stockton-on-Tees]] iron works where a relative was a partner. Dorman started as a [[puddling (metallurgy)|puddler]] and rapidly progressed in his career. In 1875, he went into partnership with [[Albert de Lande Long]] to acquire the ''West Marsh'' Ironworks in [[Middlesbrough]].<ref name=history>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/46885 Arthur John Dorman at Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]</ref> During the 1880s they exploited the new steel making technologies being introduced at that time including use of [[Open hearth furnace]]s.<ref name=history/> Together they built a large industrial concern, [[Dorman Long]], which by 1914 employed 20,000 people and during the [[World War I]] was a major supplier of shells.<ref name=history/>
Stood as the Conservative candidate for [[Cleveland (UK Parliament constituency)|Cleveland]].
Arthur Dorman was appointed a [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (KBE) in 1918<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30460 |date=7 January 1918 |page=366 |supp=y}}</ref><ref name=history/> and created a [[baronet]] of [[Nunthorpe]] in the [[County of York]] on 21 July 1923.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=32849 |date=31 July 1923 |page=5238}}</ref><ref>[http://www.leighrayment.com/baronetage/baronetsD2.htm Leigh's Baronetage]</ref>
==Family==
[[File:Grey Towers - geograph.org.uk - 23299.jpg|thumb |right |200px |Grey Towers]] He married Clara Lockwood in 1873 and together they had four sons and three daughters.<ref name=history/> His youngest son George Lockwood Dorman was killed in the [[Second Boer War]], and is commemorated in the [[Dorman Museum]].
Sir Arthur Dorman died in 1931 at Grey Towers, his home in [[Nunthorpe]]<ref name=history/> near Middlesbrough. His title was inherited by his eldest son Bedford Lockwood Dorman.
