[[File:osservatorio ximeniano, modello del motore a scoppio barsanti-matteucci 03.JPG|thumb|Model of the Barsanti-Matteucci engine in the [[Osservatorio Ximeniano]] in Florence]] '''Felice Matteucci''' (February 12, 1808 &ndash; September 13, 1887) was an Italian [[hydraulic]] engineer who co-invented an [[internal combustion engine]] with [[Eugenio Barsanti]]. Their patent request was granted in London on June 12, 1854, and published in London's Morning Journal under the title "Specification of Eugene Barsanti and Felix Matteucci, Obtaining Motive Power by the Explosion of Gases", as documented by the Fondazione Barsanti e Matteucci.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u7ijYDkmZxI|title=il motore a scoppio Barsanti e Matteucci - la storia (part2)|first=|last=mirko ferrari|date=18 January 2010|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=La documentazione essenziale per l'attribuzione della scoperta|url=http://www.barsantiematteucci.it/inglese/documentiStorici.html|quote= A later request was presented to the Patent Office of the Reign of Piedmont, under No. 700 of Volume VII of that Office. The text of this patent request is not available, only a photo of the table containing a drawing of the engine. This may have been either a new patent or an extension of a patent granted three days earlier, on 30 December 1857, at Turin.}}</ref>
Born in [[Lucca]], Tuscany, Matteucci studied hydraulic and mechanical engineering, first in Paris, then in [[Florence]]. In 1851 he met Father Barsanti and appreciated his ideas for a new type of engine. They worked together to turn the primary concept into a manufacturable item, eventually developing a model suitable for mass production. Its construction was entrusted to Bauer & Co. of Milan, a company also known as Helvetica, which delivered the motor at the beginning of 1863.{{cn|date=July 2015}}
The success of the engine, which was much more efficient that the steam-engine, was so great that orders started pouring in from as far away as Constantinople.{{cn|date=July 2015}}<!--then why did the business fail...?--> Matteucci and Barsanti reached an agreement for the production of the motor with a company in [[Belgium]], and Barsanti departed for [[Belgium]] on February 18, 1864 to oversee the work personally. On the following April 19, Barsanti died suddenly, and all their work came to an end.
Matteucci returned to his previous work as a hydraulic engineer. He studied new [[hydrometer]]s (to measure the level of a river), [[rain gauge]]s, and hydraulic operations over rivers.
In 1877, Matteucci defended that he and Barsanti were the originators of the invention of the [[internal combustion engine]]. The patent registered by [[Nikolaus August Otto]] was indeed very similar to the [[Barsanti-Matteucci engine]]. This frustration contributed to Matteucci's illness that eventually caused his death, in his own home in [[Capannori]], near [[Lucca]]. The documents concerning the priority of Barsanti and Matteucci’s engine and their patents in England, Piedmont, France, Belgium and Prussia are kept in the archive of the library of the Museo Galileo in Florence. <ref>{{cite web|url = http://biblioteca.imss.fi.it/856/archivio_motore_barsanti_matteucci.pdf|title = Summary of the documents concerning Barsanti and Matteucci’s new motor patent}}</ref>
==Works== * {{Cite book|publisher= Stabilimento Giuseppe Civelli|last= Matteucci|first= Felice|title= Intorno a due istrumenti automatici che descrivono in modo continuo le curve delle pioggie e delle variazioni nel pelo dell'acqua dei fiumi |place=Roma|year= 1874|url= http://gutenberg.beic.it/webclient/DeliveryManager?pid=6284400}} * {{Cite book|publisher= Tipografia Bencini|last= Matteucci|first= Felice|title= Sfioratori a stramazzo per moderare le piene dei fiumi|place=Firenze|year= 1875|url= http://gutenberg.beic.it/webclient/DeliveryManager?pid=6274146}}
